<div class="tag">Reading & Writing · Module 1 · Lesson 1.1</div>
<div class="lesson-title">Central Ideas & Details</div>
<div class="lesson-sub">Learn to identify what a passage is mainly about and distinguish the central idea from supporting details.</div>
<div class="dur-row"><span><b>12 min</b> read</span><span><b>3</b> practice questions</span><span><b>+20 pts</b> on completion</span></div>
<div class="card"><div class="sec-title">What is the central idea?</div><div class="body-text">The <strong>central idea</strong> is the main point the author makes throughout the entire passage — not just one sentence or paragraph. It answers: <em>what is this passage mostly about?</em> Supporting details are facts, examples, or evidence the author uses to develop that central idea.<br><br>To find the central idea: read the entire passage, then ask yourself what one sentence could summarize what the author is arguing or explaining. The central idea is usually broader than any single detail.</div><div class="two-col"><div class="mini-card"><div class="mini-title">Central idea — what it is</div><div class="mini-body">The overarching point the author makes. Usually appears in the opening or closing of the passage, but must be supported throughout.</div></div><div class="mini-card"><div class="mini-title">Supporting details — what they are</div><div class="mini-body">Specific facts, examples, statistics, or anecdotes the author uses to develop and prove the central idea. They support — not replace — the main point.</div></div></div></div>
<div class="card"><div class="sec-title">SAT strategy tips</div><div class="tips-grid"><div class="tip"><div class="tip-title">Read the whole passage first</div><div class="tip-body">Never answer a central idea question after reading only the first paragraph. The main point must hold for the entire passage.</div></div><div class="tip"><div class="tip-title">Eliminate too-narrow answers</div><div class="tip-body">Wrong answers often pick a detail that's true but only covers part of the passage. The correct central idea applies to everything the author says.</div></div><div class="tip"><div class="tip-title">Eliminate too-broad answers</div><div class="tip-body">Some wrong answers make a claim bigger than what the passage actually argues. The central idea must match the passage's actual scope.</div></div><div class="tip"><div class="tip-title">Summarize in your own words first</div><div class="tip-body">Before reading the options, mentally summarize the passage in one sentence. Then find the answer that matches your summary most closely.</div></div></div></div>
