<div class="tag">Reading & Writing · Module 1 · Lesson 1.2</div>
<div class="lesson-title">Command of Evidence — Textual</div>
<div class="lesson-sub">Learn to find the specific quotation from a passage that best supports a given claim.</div>
<div class="dur-row"><span><b>12 min</b> read</span><span><b>3</b> practice questions</span><span><b>+20 pts</b> on completion</span></div>
<div class="card"><div class="sec-title">What textual evidence questions ask</div><div class="body-text">These questions give you a claim — sometimes stated in the question, sometimes as a student's argument — and ask you to find the specific part of the passage that most directly supports it. All four answer options are real quotes from the passage. Only one quote directly proves the claim.<br><br>The key distinction: <strong>relevant to the topic</strong> is not enough. The evidence must <strong>directly support the specific claim</strong>. A quote about the same subject can fail to prove the specific point being made.</div><div class="two-col"><div class="mini-card"><div class="mini-title">What makes evidence "direct"</div><div class="mini-body">Direct evidence explicitly states or clearly demonstrates what the claim says. It doesn't require inference — you can see the connection immediately.</div></div><div class="mini-card"><div class="mini-title">Common wrong answer trap</div><div class="mini-body">The passage mentions it — but about a different aspect. Always ask: does this quote prove this specific claim, or just something related to the same topic?</div></div></div></div>
<div class="card"><div class="sec-title">SAT strategy tips</div><div class="tips-grid"><div class="tip"><div class="tip-title">Read the claim before looking at evidence</div><div class="tip-body">Understand exactly what the claim says before evaluating the quotes. The more precisely you understand the claim, the easier it is to eliminate off-topic evidence.</div></div><div class="tip"><div class="tip-title">Test each quote against the claim</div><div class="tip-body">Ask: if this quote is all you know, does the claim logically follow? If you need to add information or make an inference, the evidence is too indirect.</div></div><div class="tip"><div class="tip-title">Eliminate evidence about wrong aspects</div><div class="tip-body">The wrong answers often discuss the same subject as the claim but focus on a different aspect — the cause vs. the effect, the past vs. the present, the problem vs. the solution.</div></div><div class="tip"><div class="tip-title">The evidence must match the claim's scope</div><div class="tip-body">If the claim says "most scientists," the evidence must also talk about most scientists — not just a few, or scientists in one field. Scope mismatches are a frequent trap.</div></div></div></div>
