<div class="tag">Reading & Writing · Module 1 · Lesson 1.10</div>
<div class="lesson-title">Logical Transitions</div>
<div class="lesson-sub">Master choosing the correct transition word — the connective tissue that makes arguments clear, coherent, and logically precise.</div>
<div class="dur-row"><span><b>12 min</b> read</span><span><b>3</b> practice questions</span><span><b>+20 pts</b> on completion</span></div>

<div class="card">
  <div class="sec-title">Core concept</div>
  <div class="body-text">This lesson covers <strong>Logical Transitions</strong>. Master this concept to improve your SAT score in the Module 1 — Information & Ideas section.<br><br>Work through the three practice questions below, each designed to test a different application of this skill. Read each passage carefully before selecting your answer.</div>
  <div class="tips-grid">
    <div class="tip"><div class="tip-title">Read carefully</div><div class="tip-body">Always read the full passage before answering. Context is everything — a single sentence rarely contains enough information to answer correctly.</div></div>
    <div class="tip"><div class="tip-title">Eliminate wrong answers</div><div class="tip-body">On the SAT, wrong answers are wrong for specific reasons. Practice identifying why each incorrect option fails — this builds pattern recognition.</div></div>
    <div class="tip"><div class="tip-title">Trust the text</div><div class="tip-body">Every correct answer is fully supported by the passage. If you need outside knowledge to justify an answer, it's probably wrong.</div></div>
    <div class="tip"><div class="tip-title">Check your answer</div><div class="tip-body">After choosing, verify by pointing to the specific part of the passage that makes your answer correct and each wrong answer incorrect.</div></div>
  </div>
</div>

<div class="sec-title" style="margin-bottom:.75rem">Practice questions</div>
